{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491642"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:56:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:56:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1007"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1007"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.06,0.77,0.04,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"36966"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1007"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"21653"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1783"},{"type":"tags","id":"4511"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7502"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35173"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42197"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"36966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/36966"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the clinic with a 2-week history of an itchy, scaling rash on her abdomen. On further questioning, she reports a long history of a flaky dry scalp but no associated symptoms or previous episodes of this rash. She has recently been diagnosed with bipolar disorder and was commenced on lithium. She does not have any other history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient appears well and her vital signs are within normal limits. She appears to have mild pitting and onycholysis of her fingernails, there are obvious silver plaques on her scalp, in addition to the abdominal rash (Image).\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contact dermatitis","Pityriasis rosea","Psoriasis","Seborrhoeic dermatitis","Tinea corporis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Epsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E. Psoriasis is a chronic inflammatory skin condition characterised by clearly defined, scaly plaques that are typically salmon pink or silvery-white. The aetiology of psoriasis is multi-factorial, however, exacerbations have been associated with streptococcal throat infections, dry skin, obesity, smoking, excessive alcohol, medications such as lithium, beta-blockers, antimalarials, NSAIDs, steroids and stress. As in this case, psoriasis may also affect the scalp (around 80% of cases), trunk, palms/soles nails, and flexure surfaces (genitals).\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETinea corporis\u003C/strong\u003E is a superficial skin infection secondary to dermatophytes, also known as ringworm. Tinea corporis presents with annular, scaly lesions that have a raised border and often expand over several weeks. Tinea may also involve the nails and scalp but is a less classical picture. Often the patient has a history of previous tinea infections, diabetes mellitus, immunodeficiency, hyperhidrosis and/or household overcrowding.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeborrhoeic dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E\u0026nbsp;is a common benign inflammatory condition that affects the\u0026nbsp;sebaceous\u0026nbsp;gland-rich regions of the scalp, face, and trunk. This condition is more common in infants and young adults where higher levels of sebaceous activity are present. Seborrhoeic dermatitis usually presents with thin, pale or erythematous plaques that often have a yellow greasy crust. It is more common on the scalp, face and sometimes the upper trunk. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPityriasis rosea\u0026nbsp;\u003C/strong\u003Eis a self-limiting rash that usually resolves in about 6-10 weeks. It is characterised by a large \u2018herald patch\u2019 and results in areas of hypopigmentation and a trailing scale. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E\u0026nbsp;is a skin disorder, caused by direct contact with a causative agent.\u0026nbsp;Contact dermatitis is commonly caused by occupational exposures. Its presentation is highly variable but often includes redness, blisters, swelling, dryness or scaling or changes to the pigmentation of the skin. Due to the lack of exposures identified in the patient\u2019s history, this rash is unlikely to be caused by contact dermatitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Psoriasis is a chronic inflammatory characterised by erythema and scale"],"references":["Langley R, Krueger G, Griffiths C. Psoriasis: epidemiology, clinical features, and quality of life. Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases. 2005;64:18-23. https://ard.bmj.com/content/64/suppl_2/ii18","Oakley A. Psoriasis. DermNet. Updated December, 2020. Accessed November 2, 2022. https://dermnetnz.org/topics/psoriasis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"21653"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1007"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20117"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20117"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https: